  <div id="main-container" class="main-container container-fluid article-page"><article class="clearfix">
  <header class="article-header">
    <h1>Scientists Figured Out How to Levitate a Ball Using Only Sound Waves</h1>
    <div class="by-line">
      <a title="Jessica Eggert's Profile" class="link-author avatar avatar-small" href="http://mic.com/profiles/188914/jessica-eggert">
        <img alt="Jessica Eggert's avatar image" class="no-share-btns" src="http://media3.mic.com/OTk4OTBjOGFkOCMvOGVpYkJ6RzFsODNqbFhBN3pLTEZJOElnNEJZPS8yNXgyNS9zbWFydC9odHRwczovL3MzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20vcG9saWN5bWljLWltYWdlcy9jMTBjMjM1YmI5NjljYzhkMmQwMjIzOWQxZDQzN2FmZDQ0YmYwN2MzYTU4Y2E0NDVkMTFhNTY5MDAyZjc4MzY4LmpwZw==.jpg">
      </a>
      By
      <a title="Jessica Eggert's Profile" class="link-author name" href="http://mic.com/profiles/188914/jessica-eggert">Jessica Eggert</a>
      <time datetime="2015-11-06T18:47:10.000Z" pubdate="">November 06, 2015</time>
    </div>
    <div class="share-facebook-twitter subhead">
      <span class="fb-like-container-text">Like Mic on Facebook:</span>
      <span class="fb-button">
        <div class="fb-like-top fb-like" data-href="https://www.facebook.com/thefutureisnowbymic" data-width="300" data-keen-tracking-name="subhed" data-keen-social-channel="facebook_future" data-show-faces="false" data-send="false" data-layout="button"></div>
      </span>
    </div>
  </header>
  <div id="article-body" class="article-body share-media-toolbar-block"><div class="share-media share-media-side-fold">
  <ul><li class="share-media-facebook"><div class="share-button-count"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fmic.com%2Farticles%2F128083%2Facoustic-levitation-video-new-device-has-more-control-in-suspending-objects" title="Share on Facebook" rel:gt_act="share/facebook/share" rel:gt_label="true" name="fb_share" target="_new" class="share-button share-button-medium-facebook modal-trigger-facebook k-trackable-share" data-fb-link="http://mic.com/articles/128083/acoustic-levitation-video-new-device-has-more-control-in-suspending-objects" data-keen-tracking-name="sidefold-share" data-keen-social-channel="facebook" data-popup-height="380" data-popup-width="660" data-facebook-pixel-id="6028307541336"><i class="social-icon-mini social-icon-mini-facebook"></i><i class="social-icon-divider"></i>SHARE</a></div></li>
<li class="share-media-twitter"><div class="share-button-count"><a href="http://twitter.com/share?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmic.com%2Farticles%2F128083%2Facoustic-levitation-video-new-device-has-more-control-in-suspending-objects&amp;original_referer=http%3A%2F%2Fmic.com%2Farticles%2F128083%2Facoustic-levitation-video-new-device-has-more-control-in-suspending-objects&amp;related=MicNews&amp;source=tweetbutton&amp;text=Scientists%20Figured%20Out%20How%20to%20Levitate%20a%20Ball%20Using%20Only%20Sound%20Waves%20by%20%40JN_Eggert&amp;via=MicNews" title="Share on Twitter" target="_new" class="share-button share-button-medium-twitter k-trackable-share" data-keen-tracking-name="sidefold-share" data-keen-social-channel="twitter" data-popup-height="380" data-popup-width="660" data-facebook-pixel-id="6028307541336"><i class="social-icon-mini social-icon-mini-twitter"></i><i class="social-icon-divider"></i>TWEET</a></div></li>
<li class="share-media-tumblr"><div class="share-button-count"><a href="http://tumblr.com/share/link?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmic.com%2Farticles%2F128083%2Facoustic-levitation-video-new-device-has-more-control-in-suspending-objects&amp;description=Levitation%20like%20never%20before.%20&amp;name=Scientists%20Figured%20Out%20How%20to%20Levitate%20a%20Ball%20Using%20Only%20Sound%20Waves" title="Share on Tumblr" target="_new" class="share-button share-button-medium-tumblr k-trackable-share" data-keen-tracking-name="sidefold-share" data-keen-social-channel="tumblr" data-popup-width="450" data-popup-height="483" data-facebook-pixel-id="6028307541336"><i class="social-icon-mini social-icon-mini-tumblr"></i><i-social-icon-divider></i-social-icon-divider>POST</a></div></li></ul>
  <div class="corner"></div>
</div>
<div class="article-body-content"><p class="">S<span class="comment-selection" data-editor-comment-id="bda9c0dd-861e-4d0c-bd04-8e792f3797f6">cientists</span> are continuing to experiment with levitating small objects using sonic tractor beams, or sound waves, which can suspend and move objects mid-air. A new video of the technology shows small objects hovering over a device made up of tiny sound speakers. The objects stay suspended even when the device is f<span class="comment-selection" data-editor-comment-id="71604284-875c-4760-affc-3eb1f171c673">lipped upside-down.</span></p>
<p class="">The findings, <a href="http://www.sussex.ac.uk/broadcast/read/32804">published</a>&nbsp;in <i>Nature Communications</i> on Oct. 27, involve a working sonic tractor beam built by researchers at the University of Sussex and the University of Bristol. The device can lift and move small objects using sound waves.&nbsp;</p>
<p class=""><b>How it works:</b> The tractor beam is made of row upon row of small loudspeakers that, when all the sound waves hit the given object, create a force that causes the object to levitate. By controlling various sounds for each loudspeaker on the beam, scientists can move the levitating object.&nbsp;</p>
<p class=""></p>
<figure contenteditable="false" data-youtube-id="wDzhlW-rKvM" class="embeddable clearfix embeddable-video embeddable-youtube" id="embeddable-qtrrh18" data-type="youtube">
  <div class="embeddable-container">
    <div class="lazyYT" data-youtube-id="wDzhlW-rKvM" data-ratio="16:9"></div>
  </div>
  <figcaption class="article-embeddable-attribution">Source: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDzhlW-rKvM" class="article-embeddable-source">YouTube</a></figcaption>
</figure>
<p class="">"<span class="comment-selection" data-editor-comment-id="b5a9cd22-0de3-49ac-8da5-731dc9ecdff8">Sound is a mechanical wave,"&nbsp;Asier Marzo, a doctoral candidate and lead author of the study, <a href="http://www.scientificamerican.com/video/ultrasonic-levitation/">said in a video</a> explaining the device. "When you're in a concert, and the music is very loud, you can feel your chest vibrating. Basically we are taking advantage of this force, manipulating ultrasonic sound waves to make the particle levitate."</span></p>
<p class=""><b>Not a new concept: </b>Acoustic levitation is not a new concept. In 2012, scientists at the U.S. Department of Energy's Argonne National Laboratory used the technique to levitate liquid droplets, the<i><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/13/acoustic-levitation-video_n_1881275.html">&nbsp;Huffington Post </a></i>reported.</p>
<p class="">In the past, however, an object had to be surrounded with the micro-loudspeakers, which restricted its movement while levitating. The new finding shows that scientists can levitate and manipulate a small object's movement with a one-sided beam of sound waves.&nbsp;</p>
<p class="">The research has the potential to serve a variety of key purposes,<a href="http://www.sussex.ac.uk/broadcast/read/32804">&nbsp;University of Sussex</a>&nbsp;researchers reported. It can allow a production line to function without physical contact by assembling the objects with tractor beams. From a medical standpoint, tractor beams can carry drug capsules and small surgical tools through living tissue.</p></div>
<div class="article-items"></div>
</div>
